      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>James Lane Allen (1849-1925) was an American novelist and short story author.  His work often depicted the culture and dialects of his native Kentucky, such as his 1894 novel <emph render="italic">A Kentucky Cardinal</emph>.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">James Lane Allen Collection</emph> consists of correspondence to and about, and writings by and about, the American novelist and short story author.  The collection was probably accumulated by John S. Mayfield, American bibliographer, librarian and book collector.</p><p><emph render="bold">Correspondence</emph> with  Allen consists of two brief notes from Allen to Mayfield.  Correspondence about Allen contains several letters between Mayfield and various book dealers, and two between Mayfield and the editor of <emph render="italic">Autograph Collectors Journal</emph> regarding an article Mayfield was writing on Allen.</p><p><emph render="bold">Writings</emph> by Allen consist of a printed copy of Allen's short story "The Ash-Can," signed and inscribed by him.  Writings about Allen contains a newspaper clipping from the Austin Statesman, 1925; manuscript drafts of Mayfield's article "The Cordial and Logical Mr Allen"; and a copy of the <emph render="italic">Autograph Collectors Journal</emph> in which the published article appears.</p><p></p>
      </scopecontent>
      
